In the cases where I *have* to use a file, the built-in java temp file 
generators work pretty well for getting a uniquely-built file every time.

On Sunday, September 8, 2002, at 11:14 AM, J. B. Rainsberger wrote:

&gt; On a number of occasions I have written a TestCase where setUp()
&gt; creates an object that uses the file system and tearDown() clears the
&gt; entire tree used by that object. I have never successfully had
&gt; tearDown() finish before setUp() started for the next test, owing to
&gt; the fact (I suppose) that the JVM does not block on the system call.
&gt;
&gt; I ended up doing what you suggest: I use a different root directory for
&gt; each test, usually calling it something like
&gt;
&gt;     root-&lt;testClassName&gt;-&lt;testName&gt;
&gt;
&gt; I then add a shutdown hook to clean them all up.
&gt;
&gt; Has anyone used Prevayler? If so, have you come up with any strategies
&gt; for unit testing against the Prevayler without changing its source? I
&gt; have been considering refactoring Prevayler to talk to byte streams and
&gt; having one wrapper around it that uses the file system for production
&gt; and another wrapper that keeps everything in memory for test.
&gt;
&gt; *********** REPLY SEPARATOR  ***********
&gt;
&gt; On 2002-09-07 at 17:37 Andrew Forward wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt; I am curious under what circumstances the file ssytem is too slow to
&gt;&gt; clean up after itself?
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; I have some code that crawls files and directories, so to test this
&gt;&gt; functionality I create the hierachy right in the TestCase.  I use a
&gt;&gt; special createFile(...) method to, of course, create the file, as well
&gt; as
&gt;&gt; track it in a Vector to be cleaned up on every tearDown();
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Would it be better to increment the root directory name and then
&gt; delete
&gt;&gt; all the structures at the end of all test cases?  Or would this
&gt; present a
&gt;&gt; similar problem when joining multiple tests from multiple test classes
&gt;&gt; (provided they also access the file system in a similar manner).
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; andrew f
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; ```````````````````````
&gt;&gt; A common idea is to kill a folder on the file system after every test,
&gt; in
&gt;&gt; order to start with a &quot;clean slate&quot;. Unfortunately, the
&gt;&gt; tests are too fast for the file system, so the file system isn&#39;t clean
&gt;&gt; before the next test starts.
&gt;&gt; ```````````
